01:43.724 --> 01:47.142
(narrator) After building himself
up from a poor kid from Brooklyn

01:47.144 --> 01:50.813
to become the most
powerful mob boss in the country,

01:50.815 --> 01:54.683
Al Capone now finds himself locked
up in a federal prison.

01:59.857 --> 02:04.693
But just over two years into
his 11-year sentence,

02:04.695 --> 02:08.497
Capone is hand-selected to be
transferred to America's newest

02:08.499 --> 02:11.533
and harshest maximum-security prison...

02:15.539 --> 02:16.821
Alcatraz.

02:19.084 --> 02:21.927
(Jonathan Eig) You might
ask, why do you need to send

02:21.929 --> 02:25.047
a guy convicted of tax
evasion to Alcatraz?

02:25.049 --> 02:26.882
The reason is that the prison was new

02:26.884 --> 02:29.434
and, and the president
wanted to justify the expense

02:29.436 --> 02:31.770
of building this fabulous new prison.

02:31.772 --> 02:33.472
And the best way to
get publicity for that

02:33.474 --> 02:35.140
and scare people out of a life of crime

02:35.142 --> 02:36.525
is to send Al Capone there

02:36.527 --> 02:39.228
because that's gonna
get the most headlines.

02:39.230 --> 02:43.699
(narrator) Designed to hold the
country's most dangerous criminals,

02:43.701 --> 02:46.201
the federal prison is
located on a secluded island

02:46.203 --> 02:48.787
off the San Francisco Bay,

02:48.789 --> 02:53.075
where inmates live under
dire conditions,

02:53.077 --> 02:56.328
and Al Capone is no exception.

03:01.468 --> 03:04.636
Over 2,000 miles away in Chicago,

03:04.638 --> 03:08.924
the empire Capone left behind
is dealing with a new problem.

03:17.067 --> 03:20.686
Prohibition has recently been repealed,

03:20.688 --> 03:23.939
and one of the Outfit's
most important sources of income

03:23.941 --> 03:26.825
dries up.

03:26.827 --> 03:29.411
(David Eisenbach) The end of
Prohibition presents a real problem

03:29.413 --> 03:31.280
for organized crime in America.

03:31.282 --> 03:33.332
That is, well, how do we make money now?

03:33.334 --> 03:38.086
(narrator) With Capone cut
off from all communication,

03:38.088 --> 03:40.789
his most trusted men, Frank Nitti,

03:40.791 --> 03:42.174
Tony Accardo,

03:42.176 --> 03:43.792
and Paul Ricca,

03:43.794 --> 03:46.545
know they desperately
need to keep his organization

03:46.547 --> 03:50.265
from completely collapsing
until their boss returns.

03:53.270 --> 03:55.270
So Nitti, the oldest

03:55.272 --> 03:59.141
and most established of
Capone's inner circle

03:59.143 --> 04:01.977
takes the reins of the Outfit.

04:05.316 --> 04:07.649
("Nitti") We have no revenue, okay?

04:07.651 --> 04:09.318
("Accardo") We do have revenue.

04:09.320 --> 04:10.986
There are hundreds of card games

04:10.988 --> 04:12.454
all over the city.

04:12.456 --> 04:14.489
Dice games on every corner.

04:14.491 --> 04:16.625
We're not gonna
replace the bootlegging revenue

04:16.627 --> 04:18.377
with card games.

04:18.379 --> 04:21.880
You think it'll be
enough to pay off the cops?

04:21.882 --> 04:23.916
Hmm? The judges?

04:23.918 --> 04:26.218
Half of City Hall?

04:28.005 --> 04:29.388
No.

04:34.011 --> 04:36.061
People aren't spending money.

04:36.063 --> 04:39.064
Not on food, not on
clothing, not on gambling.

04:41.352 --> 04:43.685
But they'll still drop
a quarter for one thing

04:43.687 --> 04:45.103
without even thinking about it.

04:48.325 --> 04:50.192
The movies.

04:52.029 --> 04:53.612
What?

04:53.614 --> 04:55.364
You want to go into
the movie business now?

04:56.533 --> 04:58.033
(chuckles)

05:00.704 --> 05:03.038
No.

05:03.040 --> 05:05.123
I want to hold it hostage.

05:05.125 --> 05:10.929
♪ ♪

05:10.931 --> 05:15.100
(narrator) With Americans now
flocking to theaters by the thousands,

05:15.102 --> 05:19.521
the movie business is raking
in millions of dollars a month.

05:19.523 --> 05:21.723
(Michael Green) Hollywood
is just bursting.

05:21.725 --> 05:23.642
So for the Outfit, it means

05:23.644 --> 05:25.394
there's a lot of opportunity out there,

05:25.396 --> 05:27.229
and they're going to
target the opportunity.

05:29.867 --> 05:32.200
(narrator) To take
advantage of Hollywood,

05:32.202 --> 05:36.038
Nitti recruits a ruthless street
thug with a reputation

05:36.040 --> 05:39.124
for shaking down small
businesses in Chicago.

05:42.913 --> 05:46.298
His name is Willie Bioff.

05:46.300 --> 05:50.002
(Green) Willie Bioff is a Jewish
kid from the streets of Chicago

05:50.004 --> 05:54.256
who is accepted into
high-ranking places

05:54.258 --> 05:56.258
by guys like Frank Nitti.

05:58.429 --> 06:01.396
(narrator) Bioff has been
extorting local cinemas

06:01.398 --> 06:04.566
by forcing their
projectionists to go on strike

06:04.568 --> 06:07.903
unless theaters agree
to pay him a major fee.

06:10.908 --> 06:15.160
And now, Nitti wants to use
the same tactic in Hollywood.

06:22.086 --> 06:25.037
("Bioff") If the
theater owners don't pay,

06:25.039 --> 06:27.089
their projectionists don't show up.

06:29.293 --> 06:32.461
You can't show a movie
without a projectionist.

06:35.883 --> 06:37.966
We're interested in the studios.

06:37.968 --> 06:39.801
The studios?

06:41.388 --> 06:42.521
Which ones?

06:42.523 --> 06:43.889
("Nitti") Paramount.

06:43.891 --> 06:46.191
Warner Bros., Fox, all of them.

06:48.145 --> 06:50.729
You'll negotiate the
terms and collect the payments.

06:52.866 --> 06:55.067
You think you can handle it?

06:56.787 --> 07:00.155
Yeah, I can handle it.

07:01.375 --> 07:02.574
Good.

07:10.167 --> 07:11.883
("Ricca") I trust you, you know that.

07:11.885 --> 07:13.335
I just don't trust this guy.

07:13.337 --> 07:15.971
I don't know. Well,
he knows the business.

07:15.973 --> 07:17.839
What business?

07:17.841 --> 07:19.641
Union business, the movie business.

07:19.643 --> 07:21.843
He's been in the racket,
but he hasn't been in Hollywood.

07:21.845 --> 07:23.929
Yeah, I know that, but
it's the same business.

07:23.931 --> 07:25.514
Essentially it's the same business.

07:25.516 --> 07:28.266
You know what that
business does to people, though.

07:28.268 --> 07:30.435
Flashy, everything out in the open.

07:30.437 --> 07:31.686
You know that.

07:31.688 --> 07:33.105
He'll be fine.

07:33.107 --> 07:34.739
You know that if anything happens,

07:34.741 --> 07:37.025
it's gonna be on your head.

07:37.027 --> 07:39.027
Not mine or Joe.

07:40.864 --> 07:43.665
(narrator) While Nitti may
have confidence in Bioff,

07:43.667 --> 07:47.419
Paul Ricca has reservations about
using a low-level gangster

07:47.421 --> 07:49.588
in such a high-profile position.

07:51.425 --> 07:55.760
With few options to
maintain their empire,

07:55.762 --> 07:59.431
Ricca and Nitti know the
fate of their organization

07:59.433 --> 08:01.800
rests with Willie Bioff.

08:09.535 --> 08:11.501
(bell ringing)

08:14.339 --> 08:17.174
(narrator) With Al Capone
locked away in jail,

08:17.176 --> 08:20.794
acting boss of the
Chicago Outfit Frank Nitti

08:20.796 --> 08:23.180
sends street thug Willie Bioff

08:23.182 --> 08:26.132
to infiltrate Hollywood's labor unions.

08:42.451 --> 08:44.234
You here to see me?

08:46.488 --> 08:48.238
(grunting)

08:51.743 --> 08:53.543
(man groaning)

08:53.545 --> 08:57.214
(Eisenbach) The most famous
of the labor extortion rackets

08:57.216 --> 09:00.500
is, of course, what
happened in Hollywood,

09:00.502 --> 09:02.502
when the syndicate, Chicago,

09:02.504 --> 09:06.756
was able to take over
the unions making movies.

09:09.811 --> 09:13.230
(narrator) Once Bioff muscles his
way into a high-ranking position

09:13.232 --> 09:16.433
in the film industry's largest union,

09:16.435 --> 09:18.768
he uses his power to threaten strikes

09:18.770 --> 09:22.072
on Hollywood productions,

09:22.074 --> 09:26.159
unless the executives agree
to pay the Outfit big money.

09:26.161 --> 09:27.661
Willie.

09:27.663 --> 09:28.828
Mr. Warner.

09:28.830 --> 09:30.530
It's all there.

09:30.532 --> 09:34.000
Always a pleasure.

09:34.002 --> 09:37.587
♪ ♪

09:43.045 --> 09:47.297
(narrator) With each shakedown
bringing in upwards of $50,000,

09:47.299 --> 09:52.636
Bioff begins leading the
Hollywood high life...

09:52.638 --> 09:55.972
buying fancy cars,

09:55.974 --> 09:58.975
building a lavish home...

10:02.648 --> 10:06.399
...and running up
tabs at celebrity hotspots.

10:10.289 --> 10:13.907
Bioff gets a little too
big for his britches.

10:13.909 --> 10:16.993
There are people in the
Outfit who occasionally do this.

10:16.995 --> 10:19.079
They begin to think they're big enough

10:19.081 --> 10:21.164
to get away with being seen,

10:21.166 --> 10:25.585
with being part of the
community, of high society.

10:25.587 --> 10:28.338
(narrator) Despite his high profile,

10:28.340 --> 10:30.590
Bioff's operation is bringing millions

10:30.592 --> 10:32.759
back to Nitti and Ricca.

10:32.761 --> 10:35.762
(music playing over dialogue)

10:42.070 --> 10:46.990
(narrator) But while the Outfit
leaders are enjoying success,

10:46.992 --> 10:50.944
one man is feeling looked over.

10:53.198 --> 10:55.448
For years, Tony Accardo worked

10:55.450 --> 10:58.284
as Al Capone's bodyguard and enforcer.

10:58.286 --> 11:00.787
(whistling)

11:00.789 --> 11:02.172
(grunts)

11:05.844 --> 11:08.962
(narrator) But with
the mob kingpin in jail,

11:08.964 --> 11:13.216
the man known as "Joe Batters"
is worried he'll be left behind

11:13.218 --> 11:16.019
if he doesn't start
bringing in money himself.

11:19.558 --> 11:23.309
(Frank Cullotta) There's a
misunderstanding about gaining more power

11:23.311 --> 11:25.061
in the Chicago Outfit.

11:25.063 --> 11:27.564
It's not that you had to go
out and get notches on your gun

11:27.566 --> 11:29.282
in killing people.

11:29.284 --> 11:32.318
If you're bringing a lot of
money into the organization,

11:32.320 --> 11:34.537
that gives you power.

11:39.327 --> 11:43.129
(narrator) While Nitti and
Ricca focus on Hollywood,

11:43.131 --> 11:44.664
Accardo sees an opportunity

11:44.666 --> 11:50.170
to break into a new racket in Chicago...

11:50.172 --> 11:52.005
slot machines.

11:54.843 --> 11:56.810
("Accardo") I'll ask you one more time,

11:56.812 --> 12:01.347
yes or no?

12:01.349 --> 12:02.849
I told ya, no.

12:04.519 --> 12:06.352
I tried.

12:06.354 --> 12:08.071
(grunts, groans)

12:15.280 --> 12:17.030
Yes or no?

12:18.366 --> 12:19.833
Yes.

12:19.835 --> 12:22.202
Thank you.

12:24.206 --> 12:28.508
(Nathan Thompson) Tony Accardo
started out as a muscle guy.

12:28.510 --> 12:32.545
Known killer, known tough guy.

12:32.547 --> 12:36.633
So by the time he's ready to ascend
to the leadership level,

12:36.635 --> 12:40.970
he's a very focused and
a very feared man.

12:47.896 --> 12:50.063
How we doin'?

12:50.065 --> 12:51.614
It's trickling in.

12:51.616 --> 12:53.066
(coins jingling)

12:55.287 --> 12:59.322
(narrator) For guidance, Accardo turns
to the Outfit's second in command,

12:59.324 --> 13:01.875
Paul Ricca.

13:01.877 --> 13:05.161
(John Binder) Accardo and Ricca
were close their entire lives.

13:05.163 --> 13:07.630
I mean, they both go all the way back.

13:09.334 --> 13:10.967
(narrator) Working together,

13:10.969 --> 13:13.419
Accardo and Ricca
build a network of slots

13:13.421 --> 13:16.589
in Chicago bars.

13:16.591 --> 13:19.092
While it only costs a nickel a game,

13:19.094 --> 13:22.095
even the lowest paid workers
are able to play the slots.

13:25.734 --> 13:29.936
And a single machine is able
to bring in up to $20,000 a year.

13:33.358 --> 13:35.775
("Nitti") Ten grand, ten grand,

13:35.777 --> 13:37.360
a hundred, five grand.

13:37.362 --> 13:39.779
That's a lot of money, huh?

13:41.500 --> 13:43.867
(narrator) By the end of 1939,

13:43.869 --> 13:47.370
Accardo is proving himself as an earner.

13:47.372 --> 13:51.791
And with Nitti as acting
boss and Ricca as his number two,

13:51.793 --> 13:55.428
the Outfit is bringing in more
money than ever before.

13:55.430 --> 13:57.430
Salud.

13:57.432 --> 13:58.848
Salud. Salud.

14:00.101 --> 14:01.968
(narrator) As the profits roll in,

14:01.970 --> 14:04.470
they soon get even better news.

14:14.566 --> 14:18.618
After spending over seven
years in federal prison,

14:18.620 --> 14:20.653
Al Capone is released.

14:36.638 --> 14:41.174
But the ruthless Chicago
kingpin is a shell of his former self...

14:45.397 --> 14:47.647
...as years of frequenting prostitutes

14:47.649 --> 14:50.149
has finally caught up with him

14:50.151 --> 14:54.437
in the form of a debilitating disease...

14:54.439 --> 14:56.189
syphilis.

14:59.578 --> 15:02.612
(Eig) Capone had syphilis from
before the time he was married,

15:02.614 --> 15:05.415
and in Atlanta, the penitentiary there,

15:05.417 --> 15:07.700
he was already
diagnosed with tertiary syphilis.

15:09.454 --> 15:11.454
By the time he got out of jail in 1939,

15:11.456 --> 15:14.040
he was really starting to slip mentally.

15:20.882 --> 15:22.599
(car engine sputtering)

15:29.941 --> 15:33.059
(narrator) After rounds
of experimental treatments,

15:33.061 --> 15:36.646
Capone moves to his estate in Miami

15:36.648 --> 15:40.566
to live under the care
of his wife and family.

15:40.568 --> 15:43.820
(Laurence Bergreen) At that time,
there was no known cure for syphilis.

15:43.822 --> 15:46.906
Finally, sulfa drugs
came along and penicillin,

15:46.908 --> 15:48.658
but that wasn't until the 1940s.

15:48.660 --> 15:51.544
At that point, he was in a cloud.

15:51.546 --> 15:54.631
He was unable to rescue himself.

15:54.633 --> 15:57.050
He was just in a fog of dementia.

16:00.639 --> 16:02.839
(narrator) For Capone's top lieutenants,

16:02.841 --> 16:06.759
losing the man who taught
them everything is devastating.

16:11.599 --> 16:13.433
But little do they know,

16:13.435 --> 16:17.270
things are about to
go from bad to worse.

16:26.315 --> 16:28.282
(narrator) For the past five years,

16:28.284 --> 16:30.150
Willie Bioff has been shaking down

16:30.152 --> 16:32.569
some of Hollywood's biggest studios.

16:32.571 --> 16:35.038
Always a pleasure.

16:35.040 --> 16:38.292
(narrator) But as the
flashy mobster gets greedier,

16:38.294 --> 16:42.546
he's soon linked to growing corruption
in the film industry,

16:42.548 --> 16:47.668
and the mafia's key
player in Hollywood is arrested.

16:47.670 --> 16:50.087
(Eisenbach) This is an
incredible disaster, right?

16:50.089 --> 16:52.806
You know, one of your
top guys goes to jail.

16:52.808 --> 16:56.894
You've got now the heat of
the media glare on you,

16:56.896 --> 17:01.899
and now this is a
major federal investigation.

17:01.901 --> 17:03.901
This was terrible for the Chicago mob.

17:07.439 --> 17:09.356
(man) We know you're just the middleman.

17:09.358 --> 17:13.109
Just doing your job.

17:13.112 --> 17:15.779
We need the ones pulling the strings.

17:18.166 --> 17:20.784
I haven't got any names.

17:20.786 --> 17:23.787
Ten years is a long
time to spend in prison.

17:25.374 --> 17:26.486
No names, no deal.

17:30.109 --> 17:33.013
(Frank Calabrese) Rat is
the lowest form of life.

17:33.015 --> 17:36.383
It's worse than being
dead, worse than being killed.

17:36.385 --> 17:39.436
It's something that
nobody ever wants to be.

17:46.278 --> 17:48.395
Frank Nitti.

17:48.397 --> 17:51.281
And, uh, Paul Ricca.

18:08.083 --> 18:12.002
(narrator) When word gets back
to Chicago that Bioff is talking,

18:12.004 --> 18:15.222
Ricca and Accardo know the investigation

18:15.224 --> 18:17.474
could take down the entire Outfit.

18:17.476 --> 18:21.762
So the two men band
together and make a bold move.

18:33.826 --> 18:35.442
So you wanted to talk?

18:36.662 --> 18:38.278
This Bioff business...

18:38.280 --> 18:39.446
What about it?

18:42.117 --> 18:44.284
Someone's gonna have to take the fall.

18:46.755 --> 18:47.954
I've done my time.

18:49.541 --> 18:51.625
You're the reason we're in this mess.

18:51.627 --> 18:53.877
So now we're pointing fingers?

18:53.879 --> 18:55.629
You're the one who got
us involved in Hollywood.

18:55.631 --> 18:57.264
You're the one who brought in Bioff.

18:57.266 --> 18:59.883
What I did, I did for the Outfit.

18:59.885 --> 19:02.269
You're gonna turn yourself in tomorrow.

19:02.271 --> 19:05.305
We'll make sure you
get the best lawyers.

19:06.892 --> 19:11.111
I told you already, I've done my time.

19:11.113 --> 19:12.612
I'm not going back in there.

19:12.614 --> 19:14.731
I'm not taking the fall for this.

19:16.702 --> 19:19.069
We're not asking.

19:24.626 --> 19:28.161
(Hillel Levin) Frank Nitti was
really not such a tough guy.

19:28.163 --> 19:30.163
He did not want to go back to prison,

19:30.165 --> 19:33.383
and he came undone.

19:36.422 --> 19:39.840
♪ ♪

19:48.684 --> 19:51.902
(narrator) Desperate
to stay out of prison,

19:51.904 --> 19:56.990
Frank Nitti decides to
take matters into his own hands.

19:56.992 --> 20:01.495
♪ ♪

20:01.497 --> 20:03.613
(tires screeching)

20:05.701 --> 20:07.534
(sighs)

20:34.480 --> 20:35.896
(gun clicks)

20:40.786 --> 20:43.286
(sighs)

21:15.103 --> 21:17.487
(gun clicks)

21:34.456 --> 21:35.789
(gunshot)

21:42.214 --> 21:45.298
(narrator) On March 19, 1943,

21:45.300 --> 21:48.802
Frank Nitti, one of Al
Capone's longest serving,

21:48.804 --> 21:51.805
and most trusted lieutenants,

21:51.807 --> 21:53.640
takes his own life.

21:54.860 --> 22:00.864
♪ ♪

22:06.371 --> 22:10.624
I think his fear was not so
much going back to prison,

22:10.626 --> 22:13.210
but what prison was like.

22:13.212 --> 22:17.297
He didn't like being
closed in like that.

22:17.299 --> 22:21.868
Didn't like to be in
tight, tight, tight spaces.

22:21.870 --> 22:26.256
And at the end, he became
very, very claustrophobic.

22:26.258 --> 22:30.927
♪ ♪

22:34.683 --> 22:39.185
(narrator) With Nitti dead, Paul
Ricca is forced to take the fall.

22:42.691 --> 22:45.358
And in December of 1943,

22:45.360 --> 22:48.411
he's convicted for the
Hollywood extortion scheme

22:48.413 --> 22:52.749
and is sentenced to 10 years in prison,

22:52.751 --> 22:56.703
leaving day-to-day
control of the Outfit to one man.

23:02.711 --> 23:05.929
(Levin) When Frank
Nitti committed suicide,

23:05.931 --> 23:08.515
Paul Ricca was the
next in line to take over

23:08.517 --> 23:11.518
but in his place, Tony Accardo,

23:11.520 --> 23:13.887
a guy with a sixth-grade education,

23:13.889 --> 23:15.939
had to step up.

23:15.941 --> 23:18.441
♪ ♪

23:18.443 --> 23:21.861
(narrator) Tony Accardo
started out as an enforcer,

23:21.863 --> 23:24.981
but has now become the new boss

23:24.983 --> 23:29.152
of the largest criminal
organization in America.

23:51.508 --> 23:54.593
Bulger. Here to see Mr. Paul Ricca.

23:54.595 --> 23:58.513
(narrator) Recently made the
acting boss of the Chicago Outfit,

23:58.515 --> 24:01.183
Tony Accardo looks
for advice from the man

24:01.185 --> 24:03.935
who was supposed to take
over for Frank Nitti,

24:03.937 --> 24:05.687
and the only person he trusts

24:05.689 --> 24:08.406
to advise him on
day-to-day operations,

24:08.408 --> 24:11.493
his friend Paul Ricca.

24:11.495 --> 24:13.161
(Calabrese) This is an organization

24:13.163 --> 24:15.530
where a lot of times,
a boss can be in prison

24:15.532 --> 24:19.701
and he's going to
still be a consigliere,

24:19.703 --> 24:23.288
which is a consultant, to
whoever steps in that spot.

24:25.842 --> 24:27.592
How you holding up?

24:30.347 --> 24:32.097
I've been better.

24:33.850 --> 24:35.550
How are things?

24:35.552 --> 24:38.637
You making sure
everybody's getting their money?

24:38.639 --> 24:40.438
Yeah, well...

24:40.440 --> 24:41.773
Well, what?

24:44.561 --> 24:45.944
We need something new.

24:47.564 --> 24:49.113
You're in charge now.

24:49.299 --> 24:51.816
A lot of people are
gonna be looking to you

24:51.818 --> 24:53.485
to see what you do next.

24:55.322 --> 24:57.289
If you want this,

24:57.291 --> 24:59.457
you're gonna need to prove yourself.

24:59.459 --> 25:01.493
And that means making a big move.

25:01.495 --> 25:05.630
Like finding a new racket,
bringing in some new money.

25:05.632 --> 25:06.831
Exactly.

25:11.004 --> 25:13.171
You remember Sam Giancana?

25:13.173 --> 25:15.507
Your old driver?

25:15.509 --> 25:17.892
Yeah.

25:17.894 --> 25:20.312
I heard from him recently.

25:20.314 --> 25:24.516
He said he had a few
ideas, things we can tap into.

25:26.153 --> 25:30.405
You should meet up with
him, see what he has to say.

25:30.407 --> 25:33.358
All right, I'll talk to him.

25:33.360 --> 25:34.359
Good.

25:38.615 --> 25:41.700
(narrator) Born and raised
on Chicago's west side,

25:41.702 --> 25:45.754
Sam Giancana began his mob career
driving bootlegging runs,

25:45.756 --> 25:49.007
quickly establishing
himself as a street-smart gangster

25:49.009 --> 25:52.043
with a knack for making money.

25:52.045 --> 25:55.347
But so far, he's struggled
to move up in the Outfit,

25:55.349 --> 25:59.601
because he also has a
reputation as being a loose cannon.

25:59.603 --> 26:04.389
(Binder) Sam Giancana was
notoriously off-center.

26:04.391 --> 26:06.191
He was unstable,

26:06.193 --> 26:09.694
maybe a little bit crazy, so he
picked up the nickname "Mooney."

26:09.696 --> 26:12.814
That was a nickname that
stuck with him for years.

26:12.816 --> 26:18.737
♪ ♪

26:30.751 --> 26:33.585
You were Paul's driver?

26:35.255 --> 26:37.255
That's right.

26:37.257 --> 26:39.924
He said you had some ideas for me.

26:41.595 --> 26:43.011
Okay.

26:45.899 --> 26:48.433
You ever hear of Eddie Jones?

26:48.435 --> 26:51.519
Yeah. What about him?

26:51.521 --> 26:53.605
Well, he and I spent
a lot of time together

26:53.607 --> 26:55.690
while we were locked up.

26:55.692 --> 26:58.243
He runs one of the biggest policy wheels

26:58.245 --> 26:59.661
in the South Side.

26:59.663 --> 27:01.863
That's a black racket.

27:01.865 --> 27:04.199
Nobody's been able to bust into it.

27:04.201 --> 27:06.584
Nobody's got the
connection to it that I do.

27:11.758 --> 27:14.793
His racket's pulling
in over a million a year.

27:14.795 --> 27:19.047
And thanks to his big
mouth, I know it inside and out.

27:19.049 --> 27:24.018
How to work the odds, how
to handle the bookies...

27:24.020 --> 27:26.221
and how we can get in on it.

27:31.311 --> 27:33.228
I'll think about it.

27:33.230 --> 27:34.813
All right.

27:38.285 --> 27:41.941
Just... don't think too long.

27:45.242 --> 27:48.710
(narrator) The racket that Giancana
wants the Outfit to move in on

27:48.712 --> 27:51.663
is one of the most lucrative in America,

27:51.665 --> 27:56.217
known simply as "the policy."

28:01.591 --> 28:03.450
(Robert Lombardo) The policy racket in

28:03.451 --> 28:06.594
Chicago was essentially
an illegal lottery.

28:06.596 --> 28:08.396
Put a dollar down, you get your number,

28:08.398 --> 28:10.682
and then, once a
week, there's a "drawing"

28:10.684 --> 28:13.101
and it determined whether
or not you win something.

28:15.021 --> 28:18.189
(narrator) Operating out
of Chicago's South Side,

28:18.191 --> 28:21.659
it's run completely
by African Americans.

28:21.661 --> 28:24.612
(Thompson) The 1920s, '30s,

28:24.614 --> 28:30.702
policy generated upwards of a
quarter of a billion dollars

28:30.704 --> 28:33.371
annually nationwide.

28:33.373 --> 28:37.792
The proceeds that was
generated from the policy racket

28:37.794 --> 28:40.462
took care of the
neighborhood and it helped establish

28:40.464 --> 28:45.383
many of the early,
legitimate, black-owned businesses.

28:48.722 --> 28:52.273
(narrator) The policy is
broken down by neighborhoods.

28:55.061 --> 28:58.563
Each has its own
lottery known as a "wheel"

28:58.565 --> 29:01.616
and is run by local gangsters.

29:01.618 --> 29:04.953
And the most successful
policy king in Chicago

29:04.955 --> 29:07.906
is Sam Giancana's old cell mate,

29:07.908 --> 29:10.625
Eddie Jones.

29:10.627 --> 29:12.406
(Thompson) Ed Jones was the most

29:12.431 --> 29:14.796
powerful policy racketeer
in the country.

29:14.798 --> 29:17.315
He was the king of policy kings.

29:17.317 --> 29:21.669
At one time, the Jones
family was hailed to be

29:21.671 --> 29:23.671
the richest black family in America.

29:27.310 --> 29:29.060
(narrator) Wanting to prove to Accardo

29:29.062 --> 29:31.896
that he's ready to
move up in the Outfit,

29:31.898 --> 29:35.767
Sam Giancana decides he's
going to take over the policy

29:35.769 --> 29:38.736
by any means necessary.

29:38.738 --> 29:41.439
(Thompson) Sam Giancana
was very cunning,

29:41.441 --> 29:43.741
very sneaky, deceptive.

29:43.743 --> 29:46.911
For him, the eyes on the prize

29:46.913 --> 29:52.333
is becoming a made
guy in the Chicago mob.

29:52.335 --> 29:54.536
Whatever I have to
do to make that happen

29:54.538 --> 29:56.037
is what I have to do.

30:03.797 --> 30:06.464
(distant horn honking)

30:16.977 --> 30:18.393
That's him.

30:31.157 --> 30:33.992
Giancana?

30:33.994 --> 30:35.994
Eddie Jones.

30:40.417 --> 30:41.833
What the hell is this?

30:43.720 --> 30:46.170
Get him in the car. Now.

30:51.845 --> 30:54.178
(siren wailing)

31:04.574 --> 31:06.024
Let's go.

31:06.026 --> 31:07.602
Now.

31:07.742 --> 31:10.778
♪ ♪

31:17.176 --> 31:20.033
(narrator) In a bold move to
get in on the policy rackets,

31:20.035 --> 31:23.736
Sam Giancana goes
behind Tony Accardo's back

31:23.738 --> 31:26.990
and kidnaps one of the
biggest policy kingpins,

31:26.992 --> 31:30.293
Eddie Jones.

31:30.295 --> 31:31.461
(groans)

31:37.335 --> 31:39.002
Let's try this again.

31:41.506 --> 31:43.890
Your policy wheels, your territory,

31:43.892 --> 31:46.175
and whatever cash you're sitting on,

31:46.177 --> 31:51.347
and maybe I'll
consider letting you live.

31:53.602 --> 31:55.985
Go to hell.

32:00.275 --> 32:01.858
(groans)

32:03.361 --> 32:06.446
How many times are we
gonna have to do this?

32:06.448 --> 32:09.198
Tell you what.

32:09.200 --> 32:11.501
You let me go now,

32:11.503 --> 32:14.037
and I'll pretend this never happened.

32:19.010 --> 32:21.261
(groans)

32:22.714 --> 32:24.130
(grunts)

32:31.473 --> 32:33.389
What the hell are you doing?

32:36.895 --> 32:39.228
You want in on the policy, don't you?

32:39.230 --> 32:41.447
So you shoot up a police car?

32:41.449 --> 32:44.450
I did what I had to.

32:44.452 --> 32:46.235
(grunts)

32:46.237 --> 32:48.705
Nothing gets done without my approval.

32:48.707 --> 32:50.073
Nothing!

32:50.075 --> 32:51.791
You understand?

32:54.245 --> 32:56.746
Answer me when I'm talking to you.

33:03.755 --> 33:05.838
Do you know who I am?

33:05.840 --> 33:07.473
Yeah.

33:09.010 --> 33:13.096
If you're gonna kill
me, get it over with.

33:14.599 --> 33:17.100
How much does your policy
wheel bring in a year?

33:17.102 --> 33:20.853
Two million. Give or take.

33:22.741 --> 33:24.657
I'll make this simple.

33:24.659 --> 33:28.745
You leave town, hand over your wheel,

33:28.747 --> 33:31.280
and I'll cut you in for 200 grand.

33:31.282 --> 33:33.449
Do I have a choice?

33:33.451 --> 33:35.284
This is the best deal you're gonna get.

33:35.286 --> 33:40.373
If you wanna live, you should take it.

33:44.963 --> 33:48.097
Fine.

33:48.099 --> 33:50.016
It's a deal.

33:51.970 --> 33:54.303
("Accardo") Untie him.

33:54.305 --> 33:56.139
Let him go.

34:01.479 --> 34:05.782
(Robert Grant) Tony Accardo did not
like attention being drawn to him

34:05.784 --> 34:08.484
and would take
measures to mitigate that risk.

34:12.322 --> 34:15.158
Sam Giancana would take those risks

34:15.159 --> 34:17.210
knowing that it put him at risk

34:17.212 --> 34:18.828
but thought he could manage it.

34:25.754 --> 34:28.337
("Accardo") What you did was stupid.

34:28.339 --> 34:30.806
All right.

34:32.342 --> 34:33.842
I'm sorry.

34:33.844 --> 34:35.844
It won't happen again.

34:35.847 --> 34:40.016
Jones' policy wheel. Can you run it?

34:40.018 --> 34:41.684
Yeah.

34:41.686 --> 34:45.438
I know it better than anyone else.

34:45.440 --> 34:47.023
I got it for us, didn't I?

34:48.193 --> 34:51.444
Well, that's debatable.

34:51.446 --> 34:53.696
Sure.

34:53.697 --> 34:56.364
If I give this to you,

34:56.367 --> 34:59.035
I need to be able to trust you.

34:59.037 --> 35:04.791
That means not making any
moves until you talk to me first.

35:06.928 --> 35:09.796
You first. Got it.

35:12.717 --> 35:15.935
I'm giving you something big here.

35:15.937 --> 35:18.805
Don't screw it up.

35:27.982 --> 35:32.151
(narrator) With Accardo's blessing,

35:32.153 --> 35:36.372
Sam Giancana takes over
Jones' policy wheel,

35:36.374 --> 35:40.626
and soon targets all the
other wheels in the city.

35:42.380 --> 35:46.048
Giancana and Accardo
proceeded to take it over.

35:46.050 --> 35:48.668
They cut heads off.

35:52.390 --> 35:54.243
They blew people up.

35:56.678 --> 35:58.344
These are businesspeople.

35:58.346 --> 36:01.430
But they're still men
ruthless enough and willing

36:01.432 --> 36:03.766
to murder for money.

36:03.768 --> 36:07.937
They left African
Americans nominally in charge,

36:07.939 --> 36:09.355
but they got the money.

36:11.776 --> 36:17.663
(narrator) All told, the Outfit's
takeover of the Chicago policy racket

36:17.665 --> 36:21.501
will earn them upwards of $150 million.

36:34.048 --> 36:38.551
But just as things are
improving for the Chicago Outfit,

36:38.553 --> 36:41.187
Accardo receives devastating news.

36:43.308 --> 36:44.891
Al Capone,

36:44.893 --> 36:50.313
his mentor and the most notorious
gangster in America,

36:50.315 --> 36:52.315
is dead.

37:14.768 --> 37:19.103
(narrator) On January 25, 1947,

37:19.222 --> 37:21.889
former boss of the Chicago mafia,

37:22.058 --> 37:25.309
Al Capone, dies at the age of 48.

37:30.900 --> 37:33.067
Mae...

37:33.153 --> 37:34.735
I'm so sorry for your loss.

37:34.871 --> 37:39.240
We'll make sure we look after you guys.

37:39.375 --> 37:41.876
If you ever need anything...

37:50.970 --> 37:52.470
(narrator) Tony Accardo,

37:52.589 --> 37:54.589
Capone's bodyguard and enforcer,

37:54.757 --> 37:56.891
and now the head of the Outfit,

37:57.010 --> 38:00.761
is rumored to have sent
Capone's wife, Mae, money to live off of

38:00.847 --> 38:04.432
until her death in 1986,

38:04.517 --> 38:08.486
a show of respect to
America's most infamous gangster.

38:22.484 --> 38:24.752
(Eig) I think we're fascinated
with Capone because he did

38:24.871 --> 38:27.788
what a lot of us dream of doing,

38:27.924 --> 38:29.957
getting rich and powerful.

38:34.547 --> 38:36.297
He seemed like just
an everyman, you know.

38:36.466 --> 38:38.125
He didn't inherit this power.

38:41.471 --> 38:43.020
He worked his way up

38:43.139 --> 38:46.337
and built this twisted
version of the American dream.

38:49.445 --> 38:51.062
(narrator) After his death,

38:51.064 --> 38:55.366
Capone becomes an even bigger legend,

38:55.368 --> 38:59.487
inspiring countless books...

38:59.489 --> 39:02.088
movies and TV shows.

39:03.543 --> 39:06.911
(Eisenbach) Al Capone contributes
to the romance of the mobster

39:06.913 --> 39:10.498
as this iconic American man

39:10.500 --> 39:11.966
who is independent,

39:11.968 --> 39:13.634
he's not anybody's puppet,

39:13.636 --> 39:16.554
and he's making his
own way in the world.

39:18.424 --> 39:20.174
(narrator) For nearly a decade,

39:20.176 --> 39:22.143
the son of Italian immigrants

39:22.145 --> 39:27.682
virtually ran
America's second largest city,

39:27.684 --> 39:31.652
building a massive illegal operation

39:31.654 --> 39:34.939
valued at over $1
billion in today's money.

39:36.693 --> 39:38.659
(Calabrese) No matter
where you go in the world,

39:38.661 --> 39:40.278
when you tell
somebody you're from Chicago,

39:40.280 --> 39:42.663
there's two names that
are always mentioned,

39:42.665 --> 39:45.499
Michael Jordan and Al Capone.

39:45.501 --> 39:49.921
He was and always will be a
big part of the Chicago mafia.

39:58.298 --> 40:00.381
(narrator) The empire that Capone built

40:00.383 --> 40:02.883
is now run by Tony Accardo.

40:02.885 --> 40:05.519
And months after Capone's death,

40:05.521 --> 40:09.307
another top figure in
the Outfit re-emerges,

40:09.309 --> 40:11.976
Paul Ricca,

40:11.978 --> 40:14.612
who gets released from prison early

40:14.614 --> 40:17.565
and takes his place alongside Accardo

40:17.567 --> 40:19.734
as co-head of the Outfit,

40:19.736 --> 40:22.703
which is making more
money than ever before

40:22.705 --> 40:25.323
thanks to the policy racket.

40:25.325 --> 40:28.576
(Binder) Ricca was very, very
valuable to the organization,

40:28.578 --> 40:30.411
but just because you've returned,

40:30.413 --> 40:34.665
usually you don't displace the
guy who was already there.

40:34.667 --> 40:36.667
Accardo stays in as operating boss

40:36.669 --> 40:38.803
and handles things on
a day-to-day basis,

40:38.805 --> 40:42.840
but for strategic
guidance, he goes to Ricca.

40:49.265 --> 40:51.232
Business is good.

40:51.234 --> 40:52.984
Odds are a thousand to one.

40:52.986 --> 40:56.604
Payout's 600 to one at best.

40:56.606 --> 40:59.490
Means we're keeping eight out
of every $10 that comes in.

41:01.194 --> 41:02.610
How much is it generating?

41:02.612 --> 41:05.613
About half a million a month.

41:07.784 --> 41:09.200
That's a lot of cash.

41:10.620 --> 41:12.003
I know.

41:14.624 --> 41:17.375
It's becoming a problem.

41:17.377 --> 41:20.177
It's a lot to handle without
drawing too much attention.

41:21.964 --> 41:26.434
I was thinking we'd hide
it as legitimate cash.

41:26.436 --> 41:27.802
Yeah.

41:29.472 --> 41:31.439
But where?

41:36.312 --> 41:37.835
Vegas.

41:43.653 --> 41:45.903
♪ ♪

41:48.324 --> 41:50.124
Las Vegas is a boom town.

41:50.126 --> 41:52.626
The rules haven't been written.

41:52.628 --> 41:55.996
It's the perfect spot to take
what they've earned illegally,

41:55.998 --> 41:58.049
in various illegal
operations around the country,

41:58.051 --> 42:01.669
including other gambling, and
run it through the casinos.

42:06.509 --> 42:11.345
(narrator) But there's just one problem.

42:11.347 --> 42:14.982
The New York mob is already there.

